<br>
We also had the people that would be on most raids and be helpful and willing.  These generally made up the *backbone* of the guild.<br>
<br>
Then we have people who log in every now and then, join some raids at random, and a certain few who would stay anon and PL their latest twink or just do whatever they felt like doing (grin).  These are the people that (often with no malicious intent whatsoever) bring the guild down in terms of integrity and ESPECIALLY loot allocation.  I'm not saying they aren't great players, I'm not saying they aren't great people, but attendance is a very important factor in a raiding guild and it's unfair to both the player and the guild as a whole when you have to make up on-the-spot rules and decisions regarding these people.  That's why raiding guilds stick to a tight schedule (eg playtimes), a core set of players that can be relied upon to be there when needed and a strict set of *rules* (as such) on how things are handled.<br>
<br>
I'm sure Elnots was a good addition to DG.... but the point is, DG is a raiding guild and Elnots would only have been a good addition *when he was online and participating* insofar as the guild raiding is concerned.  It's all very well being a friendly, fun person - but it's no use if you aren't around helping the guild achieve it's goals.<br>
<br>
Casual guilds are strewn about all over the place which suit the casual gamer fine.  If you want to be in a raiding guild and kill high end mobs, then you have to put in the time and effort just as every other high end guild member has.<br>
<br>
Pyra<br>
<br>
